Around the world scientists are working to find treatments for coronavirus

[Thread]

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusDrugs …

name: BBC News (World)
tweet:
There are 3 types of drug being tested:
💊 Antivirals which directly attack coronavirus inside the body
💊 Drugs which prevent the immune system over-reacting & harming the body
💊 Antibodies, from survivors' blood or made in a lab, that attack the virus

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusDrugs … pic.twitter.com/xu3gY047BU

name: BBC News (World)
tweet:
150+ drugs are being researched worldwide:

💉 WHO is running the ‘Solidarity trial’ to assess most promising treatments
💉UK has 11,000+ patients in a Recovery trial
💉Scientists around the world are looking to use survivors' blood as a treatment 🩸
 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusDrugs … pic.twitter.com/RpbFXmcHQn

name: BBC News (World)
tweet:
Some drugs seem promising for treating the virus:

💊 Dexamethasone - the steroid may cut the risk of death for patients on ventilators or on oxygen
💊 Remdesivir - the antiviral can cut the duration of symptoms from 15 to 11 days 

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusDrugs … pic.twitter.com/VUmCn35GCN

name: BBC News (World)
tweet:
We don't know when we might have a drug to treat coronavirus, but results of trials should come in the next few months 

A vaccine will likely take longer as it will have to be developed from scratch, rather than repurposing drugs already deemed safe

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusDrugs … pic.twitter.com/l1HSJRUqtq

name: BBC News (World)
tweet:
Bubonic plague is a potentially lethal infectious disease that is caused by bacteria that live in some animals and their fleas 🐀 

Millions died from it in the Middle Ages

From 2010 to 2015 there were 3,248 cases worldwide, including 584 deaths

 http://bbc.in/3f7eSrO  pic.twitter.com/iV9A6pTMz3

name: BBC News (World)
tweet:
Bubonic plague is treatable but prompt intervention with antibiotics is vital as the disease is often lethal if left untreated

Early diagnosis, using laboratory tests on blood and other body samples, can save lives

 http://bbc.in/3f7eSrO  pic.twitter.com/tDG1aytP1J

name: BBC News (World)
tweet:
People can catch it from:

-Bites from infected fleas
-Touching infected animals such as rats and mice 🐀
-Inhaling droplets spread by infected people or animals 🐕

Cats and dogs can become infected from flea bites or after eating infected rodents

 http://bbc.in/3f7eSrO  pic.twitter.com/AuwALtGGiY

[Thread]

 http://bbc.in/CV19Wuhan  pic.twitter.com/8IzW9bTHxa

name: Mashable
tweet: These sharks appear to 'glow' in the dark pic.twitter.com/JbzGTkBvOd

name: BBC News (World)
tweet:
More than 11 million people around the world are known to have been infected with Sars-CoV-2, and more than 500,000 have died with it

But where did this disease come from?

 http://bbc.in/CV19Wuhan  pic.twitter.com/e181YVvMa6

name: BBC News (World)
tweet:
The Huanan Seafood Market was originally believed to be where the virus emerged

A large number of coronaviruses are carried by bats

Sometimes they jump directly from bats to humans, or they jump from bats to an intermediary animal, and then on to humans

 http://bbc.in/CV19Wuhan  pic.twitter.com/kPS41B3Wwn

name: BBC News (World)
tweet:
On 1 December 2019, a man in his 70s fell ill in Wuhan - he was later diagnosed as the first patient with Covid-19

But it wasn’t until 23 January 2020 that Wuhan went into lockdown

 http://bbc.in/CV19Wuhan  pic.twitter.com/xuMZYHNtNn

name: BBC News (World)
tweet:
The Sars coronavirus, which caused 774 deaths, is thought to have jumped from bats to humans via the civet cat

Nearly two decades on, there was initial speculation that the new coronavirus, Sars-CoV-2, came from an intermediary host animal at the market

 http://bbc.in/CV19Wuhan  pic.twitter.com/bS4K3IkWhP

name: BBC News (World)
tweet:
This theory has been dismissed by China

According to their tests, traces of the virus were found there, but none were detected on any animal samples

They say the outbreak likely began elsewhere, and the crowded market helped to spread it

 http://bbc.in/CV19Wuhan  pic.twitter.com/Pix3vGlsbl

name: BBC News (World)
tweet:
It’s important to know where Sars-CoV-2 emerged from, in order to understand the possibility of future infections from the same animal source

The World Health Organization called for an international effort to trace the intermediate animal host in May

 http://bbc.in/CV19Wuhan  pic.twitter.com/ujTxwxazsp

name: BBC News (World)
tweet:
However, scientists agree that somewhere - market or otherwise - Sars-CoV-2 jumped from animal to human 

There has been an increasing number of “spillover” events, driven by factors including population growth and encroachment on natural habitats

 http://bbc.in/CV19Wuhan  pic.twitter.com/hYHYmuXCLp

name: BBC News (World)
tweet:
Another theory, that the virus came from the Wuhan Institute of Virology (WIV), has also gained some traction 

But none of the lab leak theories – animal virus, man-made virus, deliberate or accidental – have been backed up with any concrete proof

 http://bbc.in/CV19Wuhan  pic.twitter.com/g5UegynUeO

name: BBC News (World)
tweet:
The lab leak theory became more well known after US President Donald Trump said he had seen evidence that the WIV was the origin of the virus

But the theory has been largely dismissed by scientists

 http://bbc.in/CV19Wuhan  pic.twitter.com/gpFUJNP0N7

name: BBC News (World)
tweet:
Many scientists are now trying to understand how to better contain a similar outbreak 

There’s disagreement as to whether the risks of studying and manipulating viruses in labs outweigh the benefits

 http://bbc.in/CV19Wuhan  pic.twitter.com/kMrxoKd1uw

name: BBC News (World)
tweet:
China has agreed to an independent investigation into the international response to the virus, but it’s unclear what the remit will be, who will take part, and when it might happen 

President Xi says it will have to wait until the pandemic is over

 http://bbc.in/CV19Wuhan  pic.twitter.com/oNTBB6jryD

name: BBC News (World)
tweet:
Tutankhamun: Treasures of the Golden Pharaoh is currently at London's Saatchi Gallery

It's on a final world tour before the relics return to Egypt forever

@BBCArabic has learned the show may have broken Egyptian law which protects the artefacts

[Thread]
 http://bbc.in/3iLuZgW

name: BBC News (World)
tweet:
Gehad Abbas is an Egyptian journalist who trained in archaeology

For the last year she’s been digging for evidence on deals surrounding Egypt’s treasures

Many Egyptians are calling for more transparency on how their national treasures are handled

 http://bbc.in/3iLuZgW  pic.twitter.com/YyGjqphofO

name: BBC News (World)
tweet:
The show has been organised by Hollywood entertainment agency IMG, under a loan agreement with Egypt for the artefacts

IMG say it cost £19m to stage the London show, but 580,000+ people visited before Covid-19 – that’s already £18 million in ticket sales

 https://bbc.in/3iLuZgW  pic.twitter.com/vQvVkrAI2w

name: BBC News (World)
tweet:
Dr Zahi Hawass, former Head of Egypt’s Antiquities, is an independent Egyptologist who travels the world speaking about Tutankhamun

They call him the real Indiana Jones but he’s a controversial figure

But, he's key to the exhibition deal

 http://bbc.in/3iLuZgW  pic.twitter.com/Z4wU65shNM

name: BBC News (World)
tweet:
Sayed Said is a lawyer, who is taking Egypt’s Ministry of Antiquities to court

He claims the deal for the exhibition, when signed in 2017, may have broken Egypt’s Antiquities Protection Law dictating how and where antiquities can be loaned

 http://bbc.in/3iLuZgW  pic.twitter.com/YT8bz74ry1

name: BBC News (World)
tweet:
For every city on the global tour, Egypt’s Head of Antiquities says Egypt will receive $5m and a bonus if more than 400,000 tickets are sold

The country also receives a percentage of gift shop sales

 http://bbc.in/3iLuZgW

name: BBC News (World)
tweet:
IMG say the loan was approved by appropriate Egyptian authorities including the Prime Minister

They say the objects were part of a series, so are not considered unique

 http://bbc.in/3iLuZgW

name: BBC News (World)
tweet:
The Antiquities Protection law originally stated:

- Touring artefacts could not be sent abroad if they were unique pieces
- Only national / official institutions were allowed to borrow Egypt’s national treasures
 
In 2018 these restrictions were removed

 http://bbc.in/3iLuZgW  pic.twitter.com/gjUDmCcAnF

name: BBC News (World)
tweet:
Egypt's Head of Antiquities said the tour had economic, but also touristic and political benefits

He did not comment on its legal status

 http://bbc.in/3iLuZgW  pic.twitter.com/TAD8ldI0Wu

name: BBC News (World)
tweet: Watch the full investigation Behind the Mask:  Tutankhamun’s Last Tour http://bbc.in/3iLuZgW

name: BBC News (World)
tweet:
The timing of the tour also made some Egyptians unhappy

The artefacts will be missing from Egypt until 2024

It means they'll be missing when the Grand Egyptian Museum opens next year

IMG told the BBC 97% of the tomb artefacts remained in Egypt

 http://bbc.in/3iLuZgW  pic.twitter.com/0X3ara72ol
